  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>Electric scooters typically use one of three brake systems: mechanical disc brakes, drum brakes, or electronic (motor) brakes. This guide covers adjustment and maintenance for common scooter brake types. Brake performance naturally degrades over time and with usage, requiring periodic maintenance.</p>

  <h2>Types of Brake Systems</h2>

  <h3>Mechanical Disc Brakes</h3>
  <p>These use a brake caliper and pads that grip a rotor attached to the wheel. Found on performance scooters like Dualtron and some Ninebot models.</p>

  <h3>Drum Brakes</h3>
  <p>These are sealed within the wheel hub and use friction shoes pressed against the inner drum. Common on budget-friendly and Xiaomi scooters.</p>

  <h3>Electronic (Motor) Brakes</h3>
  <p>These use the motor itself to slow the scooter by reversing current flow. Found on most consumer models as the primary or only brake system.</p>

  <h2>Disc Brake Maintenance</h2>

  <h3>Tools Required</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Hex wrenches (Allen keys) — usually 4–6 mm</li>
    <li>Torque wrench (optional but recommended)</li>
    <li>Replacement brake pads (if worn)</li>
    <li>Rotor cleaner or isopropyl alcohol</li>
    <li>Clean cloth</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Checking Pad Wear</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Spin the wheel by hand and visually inspect the pads on both sides of the rotor</li>
    <li>Healthy pads should be at least 2–3 mm thick</li>
    <li>If pads are less than 1 mm or metal-on-metal contact is visible, replacement is necessary</li>
    <li>Wear is typically uneven, so check both pads carefully</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Brake Pad Replacement</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Remove the wheel (follow your model's manual for specific steps)</li>
    <li>Locate the brake caliper bolts (usually two bolts holding the caliper to the frame)</li>
    <li>Using the appropriate hex wrench, loosen and remove these bolts</li>
    <li>Slide the old pads out carefully</li>
    <li>Insert new pads, ensuring they align with the rotor</li>
    <li>Reinstall the caliper bolts and tighten firmly (do not over-tighten)</li>
    <li>Spin the wheel to ensure pads do not rub</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Rotor Alignment (Disc Rub)</h3>
  <p>If you hear a scraping sound when braking, the rotor may be misaligned.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Spin the wheel and listen for where the rub occurs</li>
    <li>Loosen the caliper bolts slightly (two or three turns)</li>
    <li>Spin the wheel again, then retighten the bolts while the wheel is spinning</li>
    <li>This allows the caliper to self-align with the rotor</li>
    <li>Test the brake again</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Rotor Cleaning</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Remove the wheel (optional; can be done in-place)</li>
    <li>Wipe the rotor with a cloth dampened with isopropyl alcohol or brake cleaner</li>
    <li>Wipe the pads clean as well</li>
    <li>Allow to dry completely before riding</li>
    <li>Repeat every 100–200 km or when braking feels less responsive</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Drum Brake Maintenance</h2>

  <h3>Cable Tension Adjustment</h3>
  <p>Drum brakes are typically activated by a cable running from the brake lever to the drum hub. If braking feels weak, the cable may need tightening.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Locate the brake cable on the wheel hub (usually at the rear wheel)</li>
    <li>Find the adjustment nut where the cable enters the hub</li>
    <li>Turn the adjustment nut clockwise to tighten the cable (increases brake engagement)</li>
    <li>Test braking. If too tight, loosen slightly</li>
    <li>When properly adjusted, the brake lever should engage 10–20 mm before full resistance</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Cable Replacement</h3>
  <p>If the cable is frayed, broken, or won't adjust properly, replacement is needed.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Disconnect the cable from the lever at the handlebars</li>
    <li>Disconnect the cable from the drum hub</li>
    <li>Thread the new cable through the same route</li>
    <li>Reconnect at both ends</li>
    <li>Adjust tension as described above</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Electronic Brake Maintenance</h2>

  <h3>Sensitivity Adjustment</h3>
  <p>Many electric scooters allow brake sensitivity adjustment through the control app or settings menu.</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Open your scooter's companion app (e.g., Segway, Ninebot, etc.)</li>
    <li>Navigate to "Brake Settings" or "Performance"</li>
    <li>Increase sensitivity for stronger braking response, decrease for gentler braking</li>
    <li>Test on a safe surface and adjust to preference</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>When Electronic Brakes Fail</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Check the app for error codes (see <a href="../diagnostics/index.html">Error Codes Guide</a>)</li>
    <li>Ensure the controller firmware is up to date</li>
    <li>Check the brake sensor connections (if accessible)</li>
    <li>If the problem persists, professional repair is recommended</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>General Brake Maintenance Best Practices</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Test brakes frequently:</strong> Always test brakes on a safe surface after any maintenance or adjustment.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid riding with wet brakes:</strong> Wet conditions reduce braking efficiency. Dry brakes before riding in wet weather.</li>
    <li><strong>Replace pads proactively:</strong> Don't wait until metal-on-metal contact occurs, as rotors can be damaged.</li>
    <li><strong>Use both brakes together:</strong> On scooters with independent front and rear brakes, use both for optimal stopping power and stability.</li>
    <li><strong>Brake smoothly:</strong> Gradual, gentle braking extends pad and rotor life.</li>
  </ul>

